title: For Sale:  Metro Arms American Classic II
postcontent:
I have for sale a Metro Arms American Classic II 1911 chambered in 45 ACP. I purchased this brand new in the middle of March for $415. I've put exactly 350 rounds through it. When I took it out the first two times I experienced a dozen failures to feed. It would eject the spent cartridge fine, but would not fully return to battery when feeding the next round. It was a tight fitting weapon, and was pretty cold out, and the first two times I took it out I did so without field stripping the weapon and cleaning it even though I just bought it. I field stripped it, and gave it a good scrubbing, having found it loaded with oil. A little frog lube on the rails and a couple other lubrication points, some manual cycling of the slide, and I haven't had a problem since. 



My very first time reassembling after having cleaned it, I put a slight "idiot scratch" in it while trying to re-insert the slide stop. When I say slight, I mean slight. Not one of those horrid gouges you see. I could probably buff it out in two minutes....but the bluing on the Metro Arms American Classic II isn't exactly known for being top notch as demonstrated by the bluing being worn off underneath the safety and slide stop (visible when the safety is switch to the on position and the slide is locked open). It is in very good condition overall. No other scratches, dings, or other flaws to speak of. It's not at all a bad gun...in fact I really enjoy it. I had plans lined up to send it to a gunsmith for a few customizations that I wanted to get done (trigger, night sights, mainspring housing)...but that idea has been cancelled in favor of knocking out an unplanned bill.



Here are the specs:


Caliber: .45 ACP
Overall Length: 8.375”
Barrel Length: 5”
Height: 5.5”
Width: 1.25”
Weight (empty): 37.28 oz.
Frame: 4140 Steel
Slide: 4140 Hammer Forged Steel
Single Action
Novak-Style Rear Sight
Dovetail Front Sight
Flared Ejection Port
Extended Slide Stop
Beavertail Grip Safety
Combat Hammer
Combat Trigger
Front & Rear Serration
Extended Thumb Safety
Throated FORGED STEEL Barrel

It comes with the case, trigger lock, spent casing, user manual, as well as the factory 8 round magazine (Act Magazine) and two Chip McCormick stainless steel Shooting Star 8 round magazines that I purchased. I am willing to meet in Carroll County, Whiteside County, and Rock Island County. I could meet you in the IL QC's in a *good neighborhood* 5 days a week. I would be willing to meet in Carroll County or Whiteside County pretty much any day of the week. I would also be willing to travel to Ogle, or Stephenson County as well if we can work out a day and time. All State and Federal laws apply (72 hours minimum waiting period, valid FOID card and FOID check, bill of sale). We will meet in a location that ensures the safety of both of us (i.e. no alley deals, no crap neighborhoods, would prefer a gun shop or range if possible in order for you to inspect it in a safe and lawful fashion without causing unnecessary alarm). Not interested in trades at this time. I do have additional pictures available. If you would like to see them, just let me know.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Whatcha got? Multi gun trades welcome/Willing to separate upper
postcontent:
Multi gun trades welcome, the worst I can do is say no. Whatcha got? This is a ground up project I built from an extra DPMS receiver, and the parts list is a doozy. I'll even separate the upper for the right deal (I'm actually looking for a plain M4 upper, as long as I don't hemorrhage money over it). This gun is pristine. No scratches, no abuse. I've run around 300-400 flawless rounds of green tip through it. Honestly, I went nuts building this gun, but I've got better ones, and it really doesn't get the attention it deserves. 
If you know anything about FN barrels (twice as thick chrome lining, same barrel as used in the M-249 machine gun), and heavy barrels in general, you already know that this thing is a tack driver from hell. There's a reason FN won the military contracts away from Colt- their barrels are stiffer, more accurate, last longer, and house more chrome than a Cadillac.
-FN Heavy profile Barrel (Cold Hammer Forged, Magnetic Particle Inspected), 14.5" (1:7 twist) with a pinned and welded PSA Pigsticker comp, making it a legal 16", Mid Length Gas System
-Low Profile gas block, with a rifle length Yankee Hill Diamond Free Floated rail (I also have the optional screw in end cap)
-Black Rain Ordnance Nickel Boron (NiBx) Bolt Carrier Group, with a Brownells single gas ring conversion
-Magpul UBR Stock (I also have the storage doors)
-Magpul MOE+ Overmolded Grip

I've invested just over $1,700 in building this gun, but I'm open to negotiation, just don't expect me to grab my ankles.  I'm interested in all kinds of stuff. Throw it at me and see what sticks. Cash price is $1,500 OBO for the whole gun, or $500 for the upper without the BCG $700 with.

The Colt Official Police is a medium frame, six-shot, double-action revolver with a six-round cylinder, primarily chambered for the .38 Special cartridge, and manufactured by the Colt's Manufacturing Company. The intended specific target market for the Official Police was mainly law enforcement agencies and it became one of the best selling police firearms of all time, eventually in the 1950s coming to exemplify typical peace officer weaponry.[1] The Official Police was also used by various U.S. and allied military forces during World War II. In 1933 the Colt sales catalog listed many law enforcement agencies as having adopted the OP as a sidearm, including the New York City, Los Angeles, Chicago, and Kansas City police departments. In addition many state police organizations and even the Federal Bureau of Investigation chose the OP as their issue revolver.[1] The U.S. Army also bought some of the revolvers, issuing them to military police and to federal agencies in need of a revolver for their armed agents, such as the Treasury Department, Coast Guard, and the Postal Inspection Service.

title: For Sale:  WWII victory Model S&W revolver, Australian Army issue
location: Lakes Region/Bristol, New Hampshire, United States
postcontent:
Nice condition S&W victory model revolver made for the Australian Army.  Nice bore, tight lockup.  It is chambered in .38/200 (38 S&W), which is still available at most gun stores.  Comes with original Australian Pattern 1937 web belt, holster, cleaning rod and ammo pouch, everything an Aussie officer would have carried.
These were WWII production guns which were refurbished at the Lithgow arsenal in the early 1950's then stored.  A small number of these were imported by Vega about 20 years ago, and there is a tiny import stamp.  This pistol could have served with the Australian Division fighting Rommel at El Alamein, or fought the Japanese on the Kokoda Trail or "Bloody Buna", a real piece of history.  It looks to be unfired since it was refurbished.
